        "id": "dest-23-3",
        "name": "Mahabalipuram",
        "description": "Mahabalipuram, also known as Mamallapuram, is a UNESCO World Heritage Site on the Coromandel Coast of Tamil Nadu. This ancient town, dating back to the 7th century Pallava dynasty, is famous for its rock-cut temples and monolithic rathas (chariots). The Shore Temple, built in the 8th century, stands on the beach and is one of the oldest structural stone temples in India. The Five Rathas, carved from single granite rocks, represent different styles of Dravidian architecture. Arjuna's Penance, the world's largest bas-relief carving, depicts scenes from Hindu mythology across two massive boulders. The Krishna's Butterball, a massive spherical boulder perched on a slope, defies gravity and is a popular photo spot. The cave temples, including the Varaha Cave Temple with its intricate carvings, showcase Pallava artistry. The town is also known for its stone carving tradition, with numerous workshops creating sculptures using traditional techniques. The annual Mamallapuram Dance Festival in December-January showcases classical dance forms against the backdrop of ancient monuments.",
